            <p>Consulat<lb/>
                des Etats&#45;Unis d&#39;Am&#233;rique<lb/></p>
            <p>Place de la Bourse&#44; 2<lb/>
                Lyon&#44; le 22d April 1880<lb/>
                5640<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear &#38; Reverend friend<lb/></p>
            <p>I have read in the <sic>the</sic> Record<lb/> of the 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> your eloquent sermon delivered<lb/> on the 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> day of &#91;Hebrew&#93; in &#34;Russia Romania<lb/> and Spain&#44;&#34; and though &#34;from afar&#34; I<lb/> cannot let the occasion pass without<lb/> expressing to you my vivid acknoweldge&#45;<lb/>ments.<lb/></p>
            <p>It does the soul good to hear<lb/> &#40;and alas&#33; When deprived of this pleasure&#41;<lb/> to read such discourses.<lb/></p>
            <p>They keep alive the ancient<lb/> fire&#44; the love of former years&#44; the proud<lb/> memories of the past&#59; the greatness&#44; the<lb/> glory and indestructible virtue of<lb/> Judah.<lb/></p>
            <p>Often from the pulpit<lb/> to a people so deeply engrossed as our<lb/> modern brethren are&#44; should such<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>instructive words be spoken&#44; the mind<lb/> refreshed&#44; the heart rekindled with the<lb/> love and the soul touched with<lb/> the truth of Israels mission on Earth.<lb/></p>
            <p>I thank you dear &#38; Reverend Sir &#38;<lb/> Friend and pray you to believe that<lb/> distant and absent though I be&#44; I<lb/> still keep warm in my heart of hearts<lb/> remembrances of thy generous appreciation<lb/> &#38; sympathy and watch with pride<lb/> all your works.<lb/></p>
            <p>With Sincerest Esteem<lb/>
                faithfully your friend<lb/>
                Benj F. Peixotto<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                USA<lb/></p>
        </body>
